### Iterable Basics

`Iterable` is the base class for collections like `List`, `Set`, and `Map`. It represents a sequence of elements that can be traversed.

```dart
void main() {
  Iterable<int> numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

  for (var n in numbers) {
    print(n);
  }

  // Create iterable
  var iterator = numbers.iterator;
  while (iterator.moveNext()) {
    print(iterator.current);
  }
}
```

### Common Iterable Methods

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `map(fn)` | Transforms each element | `list.map((n) => n * 2)` |
| `where(fn)` | Filters elements | `list.where((n) => n > 3)` |
| `firstWhere(fn)` | First match | `list.firstWhere((n) => n > 3)` |
| `singleWhere(fn)` | Only match | `list.singleWhere((n) => n == 3)` |
| `any(fn)` | Any match true? | `list.any((n) => n > 3)` |
| `every(fn)` | All match true? | `list.every((n) => n > 0)` |
| `reduce(fn)` | Reduce to single value | `list.reduce((a, b) => a + b)` |
| `fold(init, fn)` | Fold with initial | `list.fold(0, (a, b) => a + b)` |
| `take(n)` | First n elements | `list.take(3)` |
| `skip(n)` | Skip first n | `list.skip(3)` |
| `toList()` | Convert to List | `iterable.toList()` |
| `toSet()` | Convert to Set | `iterable.toSet()` |

### Using Iterable Methods

```dart
void main() {
  var numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];

  // Chain operations
  var result = numbers
      .where((n) => n.isEven) // [2, 4, 6]
      .map((n) => n * 10)      // [20, 40, 60]
      .toList();

  print(result); // [20, 40, 60]

  // Query methods
  print(numbers.any((n) => n > 5)); // true
  print(numbers.every((n) => n > 0)); // true
  print(numbers.firstWhere((n) => n > 4)); // 5

  // Aggregation
  var sum = numbers.fold(0, (acc, n) => acc + n);
  var product = numbers.reduce((a, b) => a * b);

  print('Sum: $sum, Product: $product');
}
```

### Lazy Evaluation

Iterables are lazy - elements are computed only when accessed.

```dart
void main() {
  var numbers = [1, 2, 3];
  var doubled = numbers.map((n) {
    print('Computing double of $n');
    return n * 2;
  });

  print('Map created, no computation yet');
  print(doubled.toList()); // Computation happens here
}
```

> **Key Point:** Iterable methods like `map()` and `where()` are lazy. Use `toList()` to eagerly evaluate. Chain multiple operations for efficient data processing.

